The Angular Material Overlay is part of Angular Material CDK and it is meant to provide `a way to open floating panels on the screen`.

The Angular Material Overlay provides an `OverlayContainer` where every overlay is rendered.

A good thing to know is that the overlay container by default is appended in the `<body>` and it has two very important CSS styles 

> { position: fixed; z-index: 1000 }

## Scenario

Not long ago I and my team needed a way to change the overlay container location in the HTML hierarchy so let's dig into how we resolved the issue.

## The problem

Some, of the Angular Material components, are using the overlay (e.g. Material Select). 

Knowing this fact we understand that everything is appended to the overlay container which means every element rendered in the overlay will be on top of everything unless we change the z-index of the container or the z-index of the element that we need to be on top of the container.

Let's say we have a fixed header and a long page where you can use a scroll.

Let's also assume we used a `MatSelect` element on the page.

If we open the `MatSelect` to choose an option and we scroll the page, we will end up with the overlay going on top of the header.

Usually, this behavior looks ugly, and probably your expectation is a little different, then what actually happens.

![Angular material overlay with header fixed problem](https://blog.bbogdanov.net/images/angular-material-overlay-hach-the-overlay-container/overlay-select-header-fixed.gif)

## Pre-requirements

1. Because of browsers and the issue of having the same default styles in each browser we are resetting the HTML styles for almost every element so we know exactly how each HTML tag behaves in every browser.
2. Because we decided to treat the `<app-root>` as the `<body>`, we void adding styles to the `<body>`.

## The solution we choose

Our overlay container to go into the `<app-root>` so we can use just CSS to trick the overlay in some situations when you scroll the overlay to go under the fixed header.

## Implementation

Knowing how Angular works we are able to change where the overlay container is appended using the Dependency Injection.

The overlay container implementation stays behind the `class OverlayContainer` so what we can do is set a provider in our application root module to use a different instance of `OverlayContainer` when an `OverlayContainer` instance is requested.

```js
 @NgModule({
    providers: [{ provide: OverlayContainer, useClass: InAppRootOverlayContainer }]
  })
  export class AppModule {}
```

> Ok, but how the implementation of the `InAppRootOverlayContainer` looks like?` you will say.

```js
  @Injectable({providedIn: 'root'})
  export class InAppRootOverlayContainer extends OverlayContainer implements OnDestroy {
      constructor(@Inject(DOCUMENT) _document: any) {
          super(_document);
      }

      ngOnDestroy() {
          super.ngOnDestroy();
      }

      getRootElement(): Element {
          return this._document.querySelector('app-root');
      }

      protected _createContainer(): void {
          super._createContainer();
          this._appendToRootComponent();
      }

      private _appendToRootComponent(): void {
          if (!this._containerElement) {
              return;
          }

          const rootElement = this.getRootElement();
          const parent = rootElement || this._document.body;
          parent.appendChild(this._containerElement);
      }
  }
```

Voilà, we successfully implemented an overlay container positioned in the `<app-root>`.

Last, we have to add 3 lines of CSS to tell the overlay goes under the header when the `MatSelect` is opened.

```css
    header, div.cdk-overlay-container mat-select-panel {
        z-index: 1001;
    }
```

![Angular material overlay with header fixed solution](https://blog.bbogdanov.net/images/angular-material-overlay-hach-the-overlay-container/overlay-select-header-fixed-final.gif)

Thank you for reading!

